name: Dr. Seuss - Myopic Women
description:
The Rather Odd Myopic Woman Riding Piggyback on One of Helen’s Many Cats

Myopic Woman encompasses elements of cubism, which was developed shortly after Seuss’s birth, between 1908 and 1912 in a collaboration between Georges Braque and Pablo Picasso. Ted Geisel’s wife had many cats and it was inevitable they would one day appear in his artworks.


Image Size:  34” x 16.5”
Edition Size:  1/850 – 850/850 Arabic Numbers
I/XCIX – XCIX/XCIX Patron Editions
1/155 – 155/155 Collaborator Proofs
5 Hors d’ Commerce

name: Dr. Seuss - The Stag of Eve & the Zorax and the Groo
description:
As Pablo Picasso’s “Blue Period” is defined by blue dominate paintings from 1901–1904, Seuss’s “Deco Period” is noted specifically for black dominate backgrounds in a number of his most developed and completed paintings from the 1930’s to the 1940’s.

Arabic editions from Geisel’s “Deco Period,” including Elephant Presenting Flower to a Bird, Pink-Tufted Small Beast in a Night Landscape and Tower of Babel are now sold out and highly sought-after.

Serigraph on Panel
Image Size: 36” x 24”
Edition Size:  1/850 – 850/850 Arabic Numbers
I/XCIX – XCIX/XCIX Patron Editions
1/155 – 155/155 Collaborator Proofs
5 Hors d’ Commerce

BONUS - Only the first 275 collectors who acquire The Stag at Eve will be fortunate enough to receive a special Secret Art release – The Zorax and the Groo - complimentary from the publisher and the gallery.

This artwork exemplifies the direct correlation between Seuss’s early pen and ink illustrations and the paintings from what is now known as Seuss’s “Deco Period.  As Pablo Picasso’s “Blue Period” is defined by blue dominate paintings from 1901–1904, Seuss’s “Deco Period” is noted specifically for black dominate backgrounds in a number of his most developed and completed paintings from the 1930s to the 1940s.

Please note, The Zorax and the Groo will only be available as part of this unique collecting opportunity and will never be available as a general release to the Seuss gallery market.  This is an unprecedented opportunity to collect a rare Seuss piece valued at $500 and only available to collectors of The Stag at Eve.

Interested collectors are encouraged to act quickly as we anticipate demand to far exceed the 275 prints in this special offer.   The Zorax and the Groo is only available on a first come, first serve basis so long as prints are available.

Both are custom framed in a black frame with archival matting.

name: Dr. Seuss - Beewatcher - framed
description:
Did I Ever Tell You How Lucky You Are? is a book that describes people in situations that are surely worse than your own.  Imagine, for instance, if your job was to watch the bee watcher-watcher who watched the bee-watcher who watched the bee.


Image Size:  9” x 12”
Limited Edition of 2500 Arabic Numbers
99 Patron's Collection
155 Collaborator Proofs

* The artwork comes framed in a custom black frame with archival matting.
